<br>
I totally agree with the decision to toss you out of the Arena.  Had I been a GM, I would have dramatically fried yer caboose as that is all a part of the roleplaying experience.  &quot;Egads an intruder!  Take that, you rascal!&quot;  *ZAAAAPPPPP!*<br>
<br>
I was on the other night for the dunking contest and I too was quite miffed that I wasn't going to be able to attend because there wasn't enough time.  I did a wee bit of ranting and then went off to be slayed... err.. to umm.. slay some Kobolds instead.<br>
<br>
Last night, while helping me resolve some 'technical issues' *cough*  Zelorixa and I had a chance to talk about that very thing.  In fact, I had many questions for her!<br>
<br>
There was little time given because they didn't want a huge event.  The more time you have to get somewhere, the more people who will probably show up.  Instead of a fun time in which you sit around for a bit and wait your turn to compete, you get to sit around for a long time, wait and wait and wair for your turn, and then you get to wait more for the results.  More entrants=more trouble/confusion/distractions for the GM.<br>
<br>
Understanding this, I agree with the decision to only allow 10 minutes to register.  My suggestion to some is that if you think you will be cutting it close getting to an event, simply don't go, that way you don't risk being disappointed.<br>
<br>
On to other things.<br>
<br>
I think that it would be nicer since we do have a lower population than the other servers, to not necessarily allow more time for events, but to broadcast them ahead of time so that people can make preparations to be in attendance.  Narrowing the competitors down to specific categories would prevent the zones from becoming too heavy.<br>
<br>
For example, I would suggest advertising battle competitions a week in advance, then narrowing the times and places to the participating levels.  20-25th level warriors will meet at such and such on this day.  26-30th levels will meet the following day at such and such place.<br>
<br>
My thoughts on things anyhow.<br>
<br>
